result.text: Zhenhai Tower 镇海楼 in Guangzhou. The fortress was originally built by a son of Ming Dynasty's founding emperor, and it is now part of the last vestige of the old city wall of Guangzhou. The tower controls the commanding height of ancient Guangzhou city, and was therefore a focus of military struggles. The cannons at the tower witnessed the British invasion in the First Opium War, during which time the city was briefly taken by the aggressors. The building is now a museum of Guangzhou's history. I personally recommend the exhibition of armorial porcelains, which are living examples of China-Europe commercial and cultural ties that predates modern-day conflicts.
